## The Latest Fiscal Year At A Glance

Data on India's Gross Domestic Product for the 2024-25 fiscal year has just been published. Here are some highlights:

-   Inflation-adjusted Gross Domestic Product was INR 18,488,380.91 crores at constant 2011-12 prices. (A crore is ten million or 10<sup>7</sup>.)\
-   This represents a growth of [6.37 percent]{style="color: red;"} compared to the previous fiscal year. (The available data spans the 1950-51 fiscal year through the 2024-25 fiscal year. That's 74 years. Over the past 74 years, GDP has grown [5.01 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Consumption spending grew [7.28 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 74 years, consumption spending has grown [4.46 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Investment spending grew [6.36 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 74 years, investment spending has grown [5.96 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Government purchases grew [4.1 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 74 years, government purchases has grown [5.73 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)\
-   Exports grew [5.91 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 74 years, exports has grown [6.81 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Imports grew [-1.31 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 74 years, imports has grown [6.76 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Net Exports grew [72.74 percent]{style="color: red;"}. (Over the past 74 years, net exports has grown [-5.53 percent]{style="color: blue;"} annually.)
-   Summary of the latest quarter: **Weaker performance than usual. GDP growth was a bit higher than the long-run average, but quite a bit slower than in the last three years. Consumption spending grew nearly twice as fast as the post- Independence average. Investment grew just slightly faster than the post-Independence average.**

